<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
<Document>
<name>Nullarbor Crossing — Eyre Highway</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Nullarbor Crossing — Eyre Highway</h2><p><i>South Australia / Western Australia · A1, Ceduna to Norseman</i></p><p><b>1,200 km across a treeless limestone plateau, including the world's longest straight road (146.6 km).</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>1155 km (717 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>2–3 days minimum</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>April–October (summer is lethally hot); whale-watching at the Bight Jun–Oct</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Extreme remoteness; no fuel for 200+ km in places; road trains; emus and camels at dusk; severe heat in summer; quarantine bin at WA border (no fresh produce)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>1162</td></tr></table><hr><p>Nullarbor — Latin for 'no trees.' A 200,000 km² limestone plateau lifted from the seabed in the Eocene, treeless because rainfall is too low (under 250 mm/year) and because the karst soaks water away through underground cave systems before plants can use it. The Eyre Highway was sealed only in 1976. The 90 Mile Straight between Caiguna and Balladonia (146.6 km) is the longest section of straight road on Earth; the second-longest is also on this drive. From the Head of Bight viewing platform between June and October you watch southern right whales calving directly below the cliff. There is no phone reception. Carry water. Carry fuel. Carry patience — the empty horizon will widen your sense of scale.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Head of Bight</b> — Between June and October, southern right whales calve directly below the 60 m Bunda Cliffs. Boardwalk and viewing platforms; a small entry fee supports the Yalata Aboriginal Community.</li><li><b>Nullarbor Roadhouse</b> — The proper middle-of-nowhere stop. Beside it is the only access road south to the cliffs of the Great Australian Bight (signposted detours every few km along the highway).</li><li><b>Border Village</b> — Quarantine inspection point — you cannot bring fresh fruit or vegetables across the WA border. Eat the apple before the gate. A 7 m fibreglass kangaroo, 'Rooey II,' guards the building.</li><li><b>Eucla</b> — Old telegraph station ruins half-buried in moving dunes. The 1877 station was abandoned in the 1920s as the dunes engulfed it. Climb the dunes for the eerie sight of stone walls emerging from sand.</li><li><b>Caiguna — 90 Mile Straight</b> — Marker at the start. 146.6 km of dead-straight bitumen ahead — the longest stretch of straight road in the world. Set cruise control, watch fuel, beware micro-sleeps.</li><li><b>Balladonia</b> — Where Skylab fell to Earth in July 1979. The roadhouse has fragments on display. The US handed Australia a $400 littering fine, paid by a California radio host.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
